AMPLIFIER_REPAIR = [
    {"q": "What causes an amplifier to go into protect mode?", "sub": "Protect Mode", "sa": "Protect mode is triggered by the amplifier's internal protection circuit detecting a dangerous condition: DC offset at the output, shorted output transistors, overheating, or a speaker short circuit.", "a": "Protect mode is an internal safety mechanism found in all modern amplifiers and AV receivers. It disconnects the speaker outputs the moment a fault is detected. Common causes: (1) DC offset — if the output stage develops a DC voltage on the speaker terminals (normal is 0VDC), the protection relay opens to prevent speaker damage. Typical DC offset threshold is 50–200mV. Cause: failed output transistors, bias drift, broken feedback resistors. (2) Shorted output transistors — failed transistors pass full supply rail voltage to the speaker terminals, immediately triggering protection. (3) Overheating — if the heatsink temperature exceeds the thermal sensor threshold (typically 80–100°C), protection activates as a thermal shutdown. (4) Shorted speaker cable — a bare wire shorting between speaker terminals forces excessive current draw. (5) Failed power supply — insufficient rail voltage can cause imbalanced operation, triggering DC offset detection. Diagnosis requires measuring DC offset voltage at speaker terminals, checking transistor junction continuity, and verifying bias current.", "k": "protect mode, protection circuit, red light, amplifier shuts off, DC offset, speaker protection relay", "syn": "Why is my amplifier in protect mode?, Amplifier shuts down immediately, AVR protect light on, Receiver enters safety mode, Why does unit shut off after power on?", "rel": "What is DC offset?, What are output transistors?, Why does my amplifier overheat?"},
    {"q": "What is DC offset in an amplifier?", "sub": "Protect Mode", "sa": "DC offset is a dangerous condition where a direct current (DC) voltage appears on the speaker output terminals of an amplifier. Even small DC voltages can damage speaker voice coils.", "a": "Amplifier output terminals should ideally carry zero DC voltage (0VDC) — only the AC audio signal should be present. DC offset occurs when a fault in the output stage causes a small or large DC voltage to appear at the output. Problems caused by DC offset: (1) Voice coil damage — a sustained DC voltage forces the speaker cone away from its rest position, causing mechanical stress and potential burnout of the voice coil wire. Even 100mV of sustained DC can damage a sensitive tweeter. (2) Protection activation — most amplifiers monitor output DC and will trigger the protection relay if DC exceeds a threshold (commonly 50–200mV). DC offset is measured with a multimeter set to DC voltage across the speaker terminals with no signal applied. Original well-adjusted amplifiers typically show under 10mV offset. Causes include: failed output transistors, open feedback resistor, drift in long-tailed pair differential input stage, or failed bias potentiometer.", "k": "DC offset, speaker damage, amplifier output DC, offset voltage, speaker terminal DC, protection relay", "syn": "What is amplifier DC offset?, Does DC offset damage speakers?, How to check DC offset", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, What are output transistors?, Can DC offset be repaired?"},
    {"q": "What are output transistors in an amplifier?", "sub": "Output Stage", "sa": "Output transistors are the high-power semiconductor devices in the final stage of an amplifier. They amplify the audio signal to full power and drive the speaker directly. They are the most commonly failed component in amplifier repair.", "a": "Output transistors (also called output devices or power transistors) are the final amplification stage in a power amplifier. They operate at high current and high voltage, delivering the amplified audio signal to the speaker load. Common types: (1) Bipolar Junction Transistors (BJT) — NPN/PNP pairs such as the classic 2SC5200/2SA1943 or MJ15024/15025 pairs. Very common in AV receivers and integrated amplifiers. (2) MOSFETs — Used in audiophile and some professional amplifiers. Common types: IRFP240/IRFP9240. They offer lower distortion at high frequencies but are more sensitive to gate voltage. (3) SanKen devices — Higher-power complementary pairs used in premium amplifiers. Failure modes: (1) Short circuit — transistor conducts permanently in both directions, causing DC offset and immediate protection activation. (2) Open circuit — transistor stops conducting, causing one-channel loss or increased distortion. Failure is commonly caused by speaker short, overheating, electrical surge, or component ageing.", "k": "output transistors, power transistors, 2SC5200, BJT, MOSFET, amplifier output stage, transistor failure", "syn": "What is an output stage amplifier?, What transistors fail in amplifiers?, Output transistor replacement", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, What is DC offset?, Can blown output transistors be repaired?"},
    {"q": "Can blown output transistors be repaired?", "sub": "Repairability", "sa": "Yes. Blown output transistors can be replaced with matched equivalent devices. This is one of the most common and successfully repaired amplifier faults.", "a": "Yes. Output transistor replacement is one of the most common and successful amplifier repairs. The process involves: (1) Measuring all output transistors for short-circuit junctions using a multimeter in diode test mode. A failed transistor typically shows a short (near 0V) across collector-emitter or all three junctions. (2) Removing failed devices — output transistors are typically through-hole components bolted to a heatsink with an insulating mica or silpad thermal pad. Careful removal prevents track damage. (3) Replacing ALL transistors in the failed channel — even if only one has failed, the others may have been stressed and are near failure. Replace the full set of matched complementary pairs. (4) Matching — for audiophile-grade amplifiers, transistors should be measured for Hfe (current gain) and matched within ±10% for optimal bias balance. (5) Resetting bias — after replacement, the quiescent bias current must be readjusted with the bias trimmer. (6) Checking for secondary faults — a transistor failure often damages emitter resistors and driver transistors, which must also be inspected.", "k": "blown transistor repair, replace transistors, transistor replacement, matched transistors, amplifier channel fix", "syn": "Can you fix blown transistors?, Transistor replacement cost?, Is it worth replacing output transistors?", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, What is biasing in an amplifier?, What other parts fail when transistors blow?"},
    {"q": "What is biasing in an amplifier?", "sub": "Technical Concepts", "sa": "Biasing sets the quiescent (idle) current flowing through the output transistors to minimise crossover distortion. It is adjusted via a bias trimmer potentiometer on the amplifier PCB.", "a": "In a class AB amplifier, the output transistors must conduct a small current even when no audio signal is present — this is called the quiescent or idle current. Setting this current correctly is called biasing or bias adjustment. Why it matters: (1) If bias is too low (underbiased), crossover distortion occurs. The transistors momentarily stop conducting at signal zero-crossing, producing a harsh, grainy distortion characteristic of class B operation. (2) If bias is too high (overbiased), the output stage runs excessively hot, accelerating transistor and resistor ageing, and may trigger thermal protection. Bias is adjusted using a multi-turn trimmer potentiometer on the amplifier PCB. The correct quiescent current (typically 25–150mA per output transistor pair) is measured as a voltage across a precision emitter resistor using a multimeter. Bias must always be set after output transistor replacement, and it requires the amplifier to reach thermal equilibrium (20–30 minutes of operation) before the final adjustment is locked in.", "k": "bias, quiescent current, crossover distortion, idle current, bias trimmer, class AB bias", "syn": "What is amplifier bias?, How to set bias on amplifier?, Why is my amplifier distorting at low volumes?", "rel": "What are output transistors?, What is crossover distortion?, Class AB amplifier explained"},
    {"q": "Why does my amplifier produce distortion?", "sub": "Distortion", "sa": "Amplifier distortion can be caused by bias drift, failed output transistors, dirty input connectors, a failing power supply, or a failing op-amp in the preamplifier stage.", "a": "Audible distortion in an amplifier has several potential causes sorted by likelihood: (1) Bias drift — as amplifiers age, the bias trimmer resistor or the transistors' thermal properties change, causing the idle current to deviate. Underbiased output stages produce crossover distortion — a characteristic 'gritty' or 'hard' texture on transients. (2) Failing output transistors — transistors near the end of their life may have degraded gain and linearity, increasing distortion progressively. (3) Oxidised input/output connectors — dirty RCA jacks or speaker binding posts add series resistance and non-linearity. Cleaning with DeoxIT solves this. (4) Failing power supply capacitors — low rail voltage due to ageing filter capacitors causes 'clipping' — the amplifier runs out of headroom prematurely. This is especially noticeable at higher volumes. (5) Damaged feedback network — the resistors in the negative feedback loop determine gain and distortion. A failed resistor can cause dramatic THD increases. (6) Faulty op-amp — in AV receivers with op-amp-based preamplifier stages, a degraded op-amp adds noise and distortion upstream of the power stage.", "k": "distortion, crossover distortion, amplifier dirty, gritty sound, THD, bias drift, op-amp failure", "syn": "Why does my amplifier sound distorted?, Amplifier distortion fix, Grainy sound amplifier, Hard sounding amp", "rel": "What is biasing?, What is THD?, What causes protect mode?, Capacitor ageing in amplifiers"},
    {"q": "What causes an amplifier to overheat?", "sub": "Thermal Issues", "sa": "Amplifier overheating is caused by mismatched low-impedance speaker loads, blocked ventilation, a dirty or seized cooling fan, excessive volume, or failed bias adjustment causing excessive idle current.", "a": "Modern amplifiers use class AB or class D output stages that generate significant heat during operation. Overheating causes: (1) Low-impedance speaker load — an amplifier rated for 8Ω pushed to drive a 4Ω speaker must supply roughly double the current. Power dissipation rises sharply, overwhelming the heatsink. (2) Fan failure — amplifiers with active cooling will thermal-shutdown when the internal fan seizes or fails. A seized fan should always be replaced, not lubricated unless the bearing is accessible. (3) Blocked ventilation — placing the amplifier in a closed AV rack without adequate airflow is a common cause. Minimum 50–100mm clearance above and below is recommended. (4) Excessive bias — if the bias trimmer has drifted to a high setting, excessive idle current heats the output stage continuously, even without signal. (5) High ambient temperature — operating in a warm, unventilated equipment cabinet in a hot climate dramatically reduces thermal headroom. Preventive maintenance: annual fan cleaning, dust removal from heatsink fins, and bias verification are recommended.", "k": "overheating, thermal shutdown, amplifier hot, fan failure, ventilation, 4 ohm load, bias drift temperature", "syn": "Why is my amplifier so hot?, Amplifier thermal shutdown fix, Receiver overheating solution", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, Preventive maintenance for amplifiers, What is impedance?"},
    {"q": "Why does my amplifier produce a clicking or relay sound on startup?", "sub": "Relay Issues", "sa": "A relay click on startup is normal — the speaker protection relay engages a few seconds after power-on. Repeated clicks, rapid cycling, or relay clicks followed by protect mode indicate a problem.", "a": "All properly designed amplifiers include a speaker protection relay that introduces a startup delay — typically 2 to 5 seconds — to prevent the output transients of the power supply charging sequence from reaching the speakers. A single quiet click as the relay engages after startup is completely normal and expected. Abnormal relay behaviour: (1) Relay clicks on and off repeatedly (cycling) — indicates the protection circuit is detecting a marginal fault condition. Check DC offset, check output transistors. (2) Relay never engages — the relay coil circuit has failed, or the protection IC is holding the relay open due to a detected fault. (3) Relay engages then immediately disengages — typically caused by a marginal DC offset fault. (4) Loud relay clicking without audio — can indicate failing relay contacts, which have oxidised and increased resistance. Relay contacts can be cleaned in some cases, but replacement is often preferred. Relay failure at the component level involves the coil winding or the contact set, both of which are repairable by substituting an equivalent relay.", "k": "relay clicking, relay noise, startup click, amplifier startup delay, protection relay, cycling relay", "syn": "Why does my amp click on startup?, Relay buzzing amplifier, Speaker relay failure, Amplifier relay cycles on and off", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, What is DC offset?, Speaker relay replacement"},
    {"q": "What is a power supply in an amplifier and how does it work?", "sub": "Power Supply", "sa": "The power supply converts mains AC to DC voltage rails (typically ±35V to ±80V) to power the output stage. It consists of a mains transformer, bridge rectifier, and large filter capacitors.", "a": "The power supply section of a linear amplifier consists of: (1) Mains transformer — converts mains voltage (230VAC in India) to a lower AC voltage suitable for the output stage. A 100W/8Ω amplifier typically requires ±50V DC rails, so the transformer secondary supplies approximately ±40VAC. (2) Bridge rectifier — four diodes configured as a full-wave bridge rectify the AC into pulsating DC. The diodes must be rated for the peak transformer voltage and maximum current. (3) Filter capacitors — large electrolytic capacitors (typically 10,000µF to 47,000µF at 50–80V per rail) smooth the pulsating DC into clean DC rails. As these capacitors age, their capacitance drops and ESR rises, causing rail voltage sag under load, which manifests as bass compression and reduced headroom. Modern AV receivers use Switch Mode Power Supplies (SMPS) instead, which are lighter and more efficient but more complex to diagnose and repair.", "k": "power supply, PSU, mains transformer, bridge rectifier, filter capacitors, DC rails, SMPS", "syn": "How does amplifier power supply work?, What are filter caps?, Amplifier PSU explained", "rel": "What causes capacitor ageing?, SMPS vs linear power supply, What causes amplifier distortion at high volume?"},
    {"q": "What is an SMPS in an AV receiver?", "sub": "Power Supply", "sa": "An SMPS (Switch Mode Power Supply) is a compact, efficient power supply used in modern AV receivers. It converts mains AC to DC using high-frequency switching rather than a heavy iron transformer.", "a": "Switch Mode Power Supplies (SMPS) operate at switching frequencies of 50kHz to 500kHz, far above the 50Hz mains frequency. This allows the use of a small ferrite transformer instead of the heavy laminated iron-core transformer used in linear power supplies. Key components in an SMPS: (1) EMI filter — prevents switching noise from entering the mains grid. (2) PFC (Power Factor Correction) stage — improves mains power factor and efficiency. (3) Primary switching transistor or MOSFET — controlled by a PWM controller IC. (4) Switching transformer — transfers energy at high frequency. (5) Secondary rectifiers and filter capacitors — producing the DC output rails. (6) Feedback optocoupler — provides isolation and regulates output voltage. SMPS failures in AV receivers: failed PWM controller ICs, failed switching transistors, blown primary fuses, failed optocouplers, and surge-damaged MOSFETs. SMPS repair requires caution — primary-side components operate at potentially lethal voltages even with mains disconnected due to stored charge in capacitors.", "k": "SMPS, switch mode power supply, PWM, switching regulator, AV receiver power supply, modern amplifier PSU", "syn": "What is switch mode power supply AVR?, SMPS repair amplifier, How does AVR power supply work?", "rel": "What is a power supply?, Why does my receiver have no power?, Can SMPS be repaired?"},
    {"q": "Why does my amplifier have no power at all?", "sub": "No Power", "sa": "Total power failure in an amplifier is usually caused by a blown mains fuse, failed SMPS, failed transformer, or a tripped surge protection device.", "a": "A complete no-power condition — where the amplifier does not respond in any way to pressing the power button — indicates a fault in the primary power path. Diagnosis sequence: (1) Check the mains fuse — usually located on the rear panel in a fuse holder. Replace with identical rating only. If the replacement fuse also blows immediately, there is a short circuit in the primary side that must be investigated before further trials. (2) Check the power cable and wall socket — verify the wall socket is live using a voltage tester. (3) Check the internal primary fuse on the PCB — some units have secondary fuses inside beyond the rear fuse holder. (4) Inspect for obvious burn damage — a burning smell will be evident. Inspect the PCB near the SMPS primary stage and output transistors for visible burn marks. (5) Measure transformer secondary voltage — in linear power supplies, check if the transformer secondary produces AC output. Open transformer windings result in no secondary output. (6) Check SMPS startup circuit — SMPS units require a startup resistor or small auxiliary supply to kick-start the PWM controller. These are common failure points.", "k": "no power, won't turn on, dead amplifier, completely dead, fuse blown, power failure", "syn": "My amplifier is completely dead?, No power AV receiver, Amplifier not turning on at all, Dead amplifier repair", "rel": "What is a power supply?, What is SMPS?, Do you repair power supplies?"},
    {"q": "Why does one channel of my amplifier have no sound?", "sub": "Dead Channel", "sa": "A single dead channel is typically caused by failed output transistors in that channel, a blown channel fuse, a faulty relay contact, or a failed op-amp in the preamp stage.", "a": "When one amplifier channel produces no output while the other operates normally, the fault is localised in the dead channel's signal path. Diagnosis steps: (1) Swap left/right inputs — check if the fault follows the cable or stays with the amplifier channel. This eliminates source and cable faults. (2) Check speaker — connect the working speaker to the dead channel's terminals. Rules out a failed speaker. (3) Measure speaker output voltage — with a test signal applied, check for AC voltage at the speaker terminals using a multimeter. Zero volts confirms the amplifier channel is dead. (4) Check relay contacts — a relay with oxidised contacts may pass no signal to one channel even when the relay appears to be energised. (5) Check output transistors — measure all output transistors in the dead channel for short or open junctions. (6) Trace signal — inject a test signal at the input and check progressively downstream stages using an audio probe or oscilloscope. (7) Check channel-specific fuses — some amplifiers include per-channel rail fuses or output fuses that can blow protecting a channel asymmetrically.", "k": "one channel dead, single channel no audio, left channel right channel, channel failure, mono output", "syn": "One speaker not working, Half the sound is missing, Left channel dead amplifier, Right channel silent", "rel": "What are output transistors?, Speaker relay replacement, What is DC offset?"},
    {"q": "Why does my amplifier shut down intermittently during playback?", "sub": "Intermittent Faults", "sa": "Intermittent shutdown during playback is usually caused by thermal shutdown from inadequate ventilation, intermittent speaker cable short, a failing capacitor in the power supply, or a loose internal connection.", "a": "Intermittent shutdown — where the amplifier operates normally then unexpectedly enters protect mode or powers off during playback — is one of the most challenging faults to diagnose because the unit may behave perfectly when cold or at low volume. Causes: (1) Thermal shutdown — the amplifier runs fine initially but after 20–40 minutes, the heatsink reaches the thermal limit. Often caused by blocked ventilation, a seized fan, or a high-bias setting. (2) Speaker-load-triggered protection — a speaker with a difficult impedance that dips below 3–4Ω at certain frequencies causes overcurrent protection. (3) Marginal power supply — failing filter capacitors cause rail voltage sag under sustained load. The DSP or output stage detects low rail voltage and shuts down. (4) Intermittent solder joint — a hairline crack in a solder joint on a connector, power resistor, or high-current trace that opens under thermal expansion. Use isopropyl alcohol and a magnifier to inspect high-current board areas. (5) Temperature-sensitive component — a transistor or IC whose characteristics degrade after thermal soak.", "k": "intermittent shutdown, random shut off, amplifier cuts out, protect mode intermittent, thermal shutdown", "syn": "Amplifier shuts off after a while, Receiver turns off by itself, AVR switches off during movies", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, Why does my amplifier overheat?, What are filter capacitors?"},
    {"q": "What is class A amplifier operation?", "sub": "Amplifier Classes", "sa": "In class A, output transistors conduct the full audio signal at all times. This produces the lowest distortion but is thermally inefficient — the output stage runs hot even with no signal.", "a": "In a class A amplifier, one or more output transistors are biased to conduct continuously throughout the full 360 degrees of the audio signal cycle. There is no crossover point where transistors switch on and off. Benefits: (1) Zero crossover distortion — extremely low THD, often below 0.001% in well-designed circuits. (2) Superior linearity — the output transistors always operate in their linear region. (3) Highly regarded sonic character — many audiophiles prefer class A due to its unique distortion profile. Drawbacks: (1) Very low efficiency — typically 15–25%. A 20W class A amplifier may dissipate 100W as heat at idle. (2) Runs extremely hot — class A amplifiers run hot at all times regardless of signal level. Heatsinks are very large. (3) High cost — substantial heatsinking, robust power supplies, and premium components are required. Examples: Pass Labs, Sugden, Luxman, first-watt designs. Most class A amplifiers operate in class AB at higher output levels.", "k": "class A amplifier, class A operation, 360 degree conduction, high idle current, low distortion amplifier, class A heat", "syn": "What is class A operation?, Class A vs AB amplifier, Why do class A amps run hot?", "rel": "What is class AB amplifier?, What is biasing?, Why does my amplifier overheat?"},
    {"q": "What is class AB amplifier operation?", "sub": "Amplifier Classes", "sa": "Class AB is a compromise between class A and class B. Output transistors overlap their conduction slightly to eliminate crossover distortion while maintaining adequate efficiency. It is the most common topology in Hi-Fi amplifiers.", "a": "Class AB is the most widely used amplifier configuration in consumer and professional audio. It is a hybrid between class A and class B operation: (1) Each output transistor conducts slightly more than half the audio waveform (the 'AB' overlap). This overlap, set by the quiescent bias current, eliminates the crossover distortion of class B while maintaining much higher efficiency than class A. (2) Efficiency is typically 50–70%, significantly better than class A's 15–25%. (3) Quiescent dissipation is modest — the amplifier runs warm at idle, not hot. (4) Distortion is low but slightly higher than well-designed class A amplifiers, typically THD < 0.01% at rated power for quality designs. The bias point in class AB is critical — it must be set correctly to achieve the crossover overlap without entering true class B operation. Most AV receivers, integrated amplifiers, and power amplifiers from brands like Denon, Yamaha, Marantz, NAD, and Rotel use class AB output stages.", "k": "class AB, class AB amplifier, bias overlap, efficiency, most common amplifier type", "syn": "What is class AB operation?, How does class AB work?, Difference between class A and AB", "rel": "What is class A amplifier?, What is biasing?, What are output transistors?"},
    {"q": "What is a class D amplifier?", "sub": "Amplifier Classes", "sa": "Class D amplifiers use pulse-width modulation (PWM) to switch output transistors rapidly between fully on and fully off. They achieve very high efficiency (85–95%) and generate minimal heat.", "a": "Class D amplifiers operate by rapidly switching output transistors (MOSFETs) between fully-on and fully-off states at a frequency typically between 200kHz and 500kHz. The audio signal modulates the pulse width of this switching — loud passages produce wider pulses, quiet passages produce narrower ones (Pulse Width Modulation, PWM). An output filter (inductor-capacitor low-pass filter) reconstructs the audio signal from the switching waveform. Benefits: (1) Very high efficiency — 85–95% is achievable, producing very little heat. (2) Compact size — no large heatsinks required. (3) Lower weight and cost for a given power output. Modern class D amplifiers have reached very high audio quality with distortion below 0.001% in premium implementations. However, poorly implemented class D designs can have: (1) Higher noise at high frequencies. (2) Interaction with speaker impedance curves affecting frequency response. (3) Sensitivity to EMI. Used extensively in AV receivers, soundbars, active speakers, and car audio. Brands: Hypex, Purifi, ICEpower, NAD M33.", "k": "class D amplifier, switching amplifier, PWM amplifier, high efficiency amplifier, D-class, ICEpower, Hypex", "syn": "What is a class D amplifier?, Class D vs class AB, How do switching amplifiers work?, Are class D amps good?", "rel": "What is class AB amplifier?, What is biasing?, Amplifier efficiency explained"},
    {"q": "What is a valve or tube amplifier?", "sub": "Valve Technology", "sa": "A valve (or tube) amplifier uses thermionic vacuum tubes instead of transistors for amplification. Tubes introduce specific harmonic distortion characteristics that many audiophiles find musically pleasing.", "a": "Valve amplifiers (called tube amplifiers in the United States) use thermionic vacuum tubes — glass envelopes containing heated cathodes, grids, and anodes — as active amplification devices instead of transistors. Key characteristics: (1) Harmonic distortion profile — valves produce predominantly even-order harmonics (2nd, 4th) which are generally harmonious to the human ear, compared to odd-order harmonics produced by transistor amplifiers. This is often described as a 'warm' or 'musical' character. (2) Output transformer — most valve power amplifiers require an output transformer to match the valve's high-impedance anode circuit to the low-impedance speaker load. Transformer quality profoundly affects frequency response and bass extension. (3) High-voltage operation — valve circuits operate at 200–500VDC on the plate. This is potentially lethal and requires respect during service work. (4) Regular maintenance — valves have finite lifespans (2,000–10,000 hours depending on type). Replacing and re-biasing output valves is normal maintenance. Common output valve types: EL34, KT88, KT150, 6L6, EL84, 300B.", "k": "valve amplifier, tube amplifier, thermionic, EL34, KT88, warm sound, vintage audio, tube bias", "syn": "What is a tube amp?, Valve vs transistor amplifier, Why do people prefer tube amps?", "rel": "What is class A amplifier?, Turntable and valve amplifier system, What is biasing?"},
    {"q": "Can a valve amplifier be repaired?", "sub": "Repairability", "sa": "Yes. Valve amplifiers are often easier to repair than modern AV receivers due to fewer proprietary components. Valve replacement, re-biasing, and capacitor replacement are common successful repairs.", "a": "Valve amplifiers are generally considered more serviceable than modern multi-channel AV receivers because: (1) Most components are through-hole, large-bodied, and easy to access without microscopes. (2) Schematics and service data are widely available for vintage equipment. (3) Valves themselves are replaceable consumables — they are not proprietary chips. Common repairs: (1) Output valve replacement and re-biasing — the most common service procedure. Matched sets of EL34, KT88, or other output valves can be sourced from specialist valve suppliers. Bias must be reset after replacement. (2) Filter capacitor replacement — old electrolytic capacitors in the power supply (often at 450–500V rating) dry out over decades. Replacement with equivalent modern capacitors restores full performance. (3) Coupling capacitor replacement — coupling capacitors between stages can go leaky, passing DC into the following stage and damaging subsequent components. (4) Output transformer fault — open-circuited or shorted transformer windings are less common but possible. Transformer rewinding is a specialist skill. Safety note: Valve amplifiers store lethal charge in power supply capacitors for minutes after disconnection. Always discharge before working.", "k": "valve amplifier repair, tube amp repair, valve replacement, EL34 replace, bias valve amp, old tube amp", "syn": "Can tube amps be fixed?, Valve amplifier service, Is my old tube amp repairable?", "rel": "What is a valve amplifier?, What is re-biasing?, Capacitor replacement in amplifiers"},
    {"q": "What does 'no audio from one channel' mean in an AV receiver?", "sub": "Dead Channel", "sa": "One silent channel in an AV receiver indicates a fault in that channel's signal path — from the input switch through the DSP, volume IC, channel driver, and output transistors to the speaker relay.", "a": "In a modern AV receiver, the audio signal travels through a complex chain: HDMI input → HDMI decoding chip → DSP processor → digital volume control → DAC → analog preamplifier → power amplifier stage → protection relay → speaker. A single dead channel can be caused by a fault at any point along this path. Diagnosis approach: (1) Verify the speaker and cable are functional by testing them on a working channel. (2) Check if the AVR's channel assignment settings are correct — a misconfigured speaker layout can mute a channel in software. (3) Check channel trim levels — a channel accidentally muted or trimmed to -∞ in the speaker settings menu. (4) Inspect the DSP or audio processor IC — in some failures, individual output DAC or DSP channels fail. (5) Check the analog output stage — measure the signal at the pre-out if available. (6) Inspect the speaker relay — relay contacts for individual channels can oxidise. This is a real-world repair scenario AHA Technologies handles regularly for Denon, Yamaha, and Marantz receivers where individual DSP channel outputs fail after firmware updates or hardware events.", "k": "one channel AV receiver, single channel AVR, surround channel dead, centre channel dead, DSP channel failure", "syn": "No sound from one speaker AVR, Single speaker not working receiver, Centre channel quiet AVR, Surround channel dead AV", "rel": "What is a DSP?, HDMI board repair, Speaker relay replacement"},
    {"q": "What causes burn smell from an amplifier?", "sub": "Burn Damage", "sa": "A burning smell from an amplifier indicates a component has overheated and is burning — typically an output transistor, resistor, PCB track, electrolytic capacitor, or transformer winding.", "a": "A distinctive burning smell is a serious warning sign that requires immediate action: power off the unit and do not power it on again until diagnosed. Common causes: (1) Burning output transistor — a shorted transistor passing excessive current heats to the point of combustion. The transistor body may be discoloured black. (2) Burning emitter resistors — small resistors (typically 0.22Ω to 0.47Ω) in the output stage conduct high current and can overheat when a transistor fails. Burnt resistors are visually identifiable by discolouration or cracking. (3) Burning PCB track — heavy current in a narrow PCB copper track causes resistive heating and track carbonisation. Burnt tracks require cleaning, re-routing, and sometimes micro-wire repair bridges. (4) Burning electrolytic capacitor — overheated capacitors in the power supply or bias circuit vent, producing a distinctive chemical smell. (5) Burning transformer — rare, but insulation breakdown in transformer windings causes a sharp, acrid smell. Transformers with open secondary windings may drive excessive primary current. Safety: never sniff component burn products directly — some are toxic. Inspect with magnification and isopropyl alcohol cleaning.", "k": "burn smell, burning amplifier, amplifier smells, burnt component, smoke from amplifier, burnt PCB", "syn": "My amplifier smells burnt, Burning electronics from receiver, Smoke from AV receiver, Component burn amplifier", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, What are output transistors?, PCB track repair"},
    {"q": "What is a power transformer in an amplifier and can it be repaired?", "sub": "Power Supply", "sa": "The power transformer converts mains AC voltage to the lower AC voltage needed by the amplifier's power supply rectifiers. Open windings can be rewound; shorted windings typically require transformer replacement or rewinding.", "a": "In linear-supply amplifiers, the mains transformer is a large, laminated iron-core component that steps down the mains voltage to the values needed by the amplifier's output stage and auxiliary supplies. A typical high-power amplifier transformer may weigh 3–8 kg. Failure modes: (1) Open primary winding — the amplifier is completely dead. Primary winding opens due to thermal stress or surge. Diagnosis: check for continuity across primary. (2) Open secondary winding — amplifier dead or partially functional. Measure secondary AC voltages. (3) Shorted turns — the transformer runs hot and hums excessively. The primary current will be very high. (4) Insulation breakdown — arcing between primary and secondary or between windings, causing safety concerns. Repairability: (1) Open winding faults can sometimes be rewound by specialist transformer rewind workshops. (2) Shorted turns typically require complete replacement or rewinding. (3) Equivalent replacement transformers can be custom-wound to original specifications by specialist suppliers. (4) Toroidal transformers (common in Hi-Fi amplifiers) can be rewound more readily than EI-core types. Transformer replacement in brands like Rotel, NAD, and Cambridge Audio is a known repair service.", "k": "power transformer, mains transformer, transformer repair, transformer rewind, amplifier transformer, open winding", "syn": "Can amplifier transformer be fixed?, Transformer replacement amplifier, Amplifier humming transformer fault", "rel": "What is a power supply amplifier?, Why does my amplifier hum?, No power amplifier"},
    {"q": "What are emitter resistors and why do they fail?", "sub": "Output Stage", "sa": "Emitter resistors are small, low-value resistors (0.1Ω–0.47Ω) in series with each output transistor's emitter leg. They balance current sharing between transistors and provide a measurement point for bias current.", "a": "Emitter resistors (also called source resistors in MOSFET designs, or ballast resistors) are precision low-value resistors placed in series with the emitter of each output transistor. They serve critical functions: (1) Current sharing — in amplifiers using multiple parallel output transistor pairs, emitter resistors force equal current distribution. Without them, one transistor would hog current while others are underdriven. (2) Bias measurement point — voltage drop across emitter resistors (V = I × R) allows the quiescent current to be measured and adjusted. (3) Thermal stabilisation — the voltage drop across emitter resistors increases as temperature rises, naturally limiting the current increase that would otherwise cause thermal runaway. Failure: when an output transistor shorts, the full supply rail voltage appears across the emitter resistors, causing momentary excessive current. The resistors absorb significant energy and typically overheat, crack, and open-circuit. Emitter resistors that are open-circuit cause loss of that transistor pair's contribution to the output, increasing distortion and stressing remaining devices. Emitter resistors should always be replaced alongside failed output transistors — they cost pennies but their replacement is critical.", "k": "emitter resistors, ballast resistors, source resistors, current sharing, bias measurement, output stage resistors", "syn": "What are ballast resistors in amplifiers?, Why do emitter resistors burn?, Replace emitter resistors with transistors", "rel": "What are output transistors?, What is biasing?, Can blown output transistors be repaired?"},
    {"q": "What is thermal runaway in an amplifier?", "sub": "Thermal Issues", "sa": "Thermal runaway is a positive feedback loop where rising temperature increases transistor current, which further increases temperature, eventually leading to transistor failure or PCB damage.", "a": "Thermal runaway is a self-reinforcing failure condition in bipolar transistor output stages. The mechanism: (1) A bipolar transistor's base-emitter junction voltage decreases by approximately 2mV per degree Celsius of temperature rise. (2) If the bias circuit does not compensate for this, the transistor's operating current increases as temperature rises. (3) Increased current generates more heat. (4) More heat further reduces the junction voltage, increasing current further. (5) This cycle continues until the transistor fails catastrophically. Prevention mechanisms in well-designed amplifiers: (1) Thermal tracking — the bias trimmer or a dedicated bias servo IC is temperature-compensated using a thermal sensor (diode or transistor) thermally bonded to the heatsink or output transistor mounting surface. As temperature rises, the sensor reduces bias current to compensate. (2) Emitter resistors — as described above, provide natural current limiting. Thermal runaway risk increases with: failing thermal compound, poor transistor-to-heatsink contact, missing thermal pads, or a disconnected temperature sensor.", "k": "thermal runaway, transistor failure, thermal compensation, thermal sensor, heatsink temperature, bias temperature", "syn": "What is amplifier thermal runaway?, Why do transistors destroy themselves?, Amplifier self-destruction mechanism", "rel": "What is biasing?, What causes amplifier overheating?, What are output transistors?"},
    {"q": "What is DC offset protection and how does it work?", "sub": "Protection Circuits", "sa": "DC offset protection monitors the amplifier's speaker output terminals for DC voltage. If DC exceeds a safe threshold (typically 50–200mV), a relay opens the speaker circuit within milliseconds to prevent speaker damage.", "a": "All quality amplifiers include DC offset protection. The protection circuit continuously samples the voltage at the speaker output terminals through a resistive voltage divider network. This sampled voltage is compared against a reference in a comparator circuit (or a dedicated protection IC such as the TA7317 or UPC1237). If DC voltage exceeds the preset threshold — typically 50mV to 200mV depending on design — the comparator triggers the protection relay within 50–200 milliseconds, disconnecting the speaker outputs. The relay is also held open during startup to absorb the power supply turn-on transient, typically for 2–5 seconds. After startup initialisation, if DC is within safe limits, the relay closes. Modern AV receivers implement this protection digitally within the DSP or dedicated protection microprocessor. Protection IC failures: the UPC1237 and similar protection ICs can themselves fail, causing either: (a) constant protection activation (relay never closes), or (b) disabled protection (relay always closes even with DC present, creating a dangerous condition). Testing: check the protection relay coil voltage with a multimeter.", "k": "DC offset protection, protection relay, speaker protection circuit, UPC1237, TA7317, relay coil", "syn": "How does amplifier protection work?, Speaker protection relay explained, What is the HP IC in amplifiers?", "rel": "What causes protect mode?, What is DC offset?, Speaker relay replacement"},
    {"q": "What causes an amplifier to hum loudly?", "sub": "Hum & Noise", "sa": "Loud hum from an amplifier is caused by failing filter capacitors in the power supply, a ground loop, a failing transformer with shorted turns, or a faulty power supply board.", "a": "Amplifier hum at mains frequency (50Hz in India) or at twice mains frequency (100Hz) indicates one of these causes: (1) Ageing power supply filter capacitors — the primary cause of hum in amplifiers over 10 years old. As large electrolytic capacitors age, their capacitance falls and ESR rises. This allows more ripple from the rectifier to appear on the DC rails, which the output stage amplifies as hum. Replacement of filter caps typically cures this completely. (2) Ground loop — hum often comes from the signal path, not the power supply. Disconnect all inputs and check if hum disappears. If yes, trace to the source device creating the loop (see ground loop article). (3) Transformer hum — a mechanical hum from the chassis itself (not through the speakers) indicates the transformer laminations are vibrating. This is caused by DC offset on the mains supply or loose lamination bolts. Mechanical hum can be reduced by tightening the transformer mounting bolt and using DC mains filters. (4) Poor mains earth — a bad earth connection at the wall socket can cause hum. Have mains earth verified by an electrician.", "k": "amplifier hum, 50Hz hum, 100Hz hum, filter capacitor hum, mains hum, transformer hum, power supply hum", "syn": "Why is my amplifier humming?, Loud hum from speakers amplifier, Amplifier buzz 50Hz fix", "rel": "What causes ground loop hum?, What are filter capacitors?, Transformer hum amplifier"},
    {"q": "What is an integrated amplifier?", "sub": "Equipment Types", "sa": "An integrated amplifier combines a preamplifier (source selection, volume control) and a power amplifier (driving the speakers) in a single chassis. It is the standard Hi-Fi amplifier for most stereo systems.", "a": "An integrated amplifier consolidates two separate functions into one unit: (1) Preamplifier — handles source selection (choosing between input 1, 2, 3 etc.), volume control, tone controls (bass/treble) if fitted, and sometimes phono stage amplification for turntables. Operates at line-level signal. (2) Power amplifier — accepts the preamplifier's output signal and amplifies it to the power level required to drive the speaker load (watts). An integrated amplifier is the most cost-effective and space-efficient way to build a stereo Hi-Fi system. The pre and power sections in an integrated amp share a common chassis and power supply, which introduces some crosstalk compared to true separates. High-end integrated amplifiers include a pre-out and power amplifier input facility, allowing the unit to be used as a standalone preamplifier or power amplifier in a separates system. Example brands: Cambridge Audio, NAD, Rotel, Exposure, Naim, Rega, Luxman, Accuphase.", "k": "integrated amplifier, stereo amplifier, pre amp power amp combined, hi-fi amplifier type, preamp volume control", "syn": "What is an integrated amp?, Integrated amplifier explained, Stereo amplifier definition", "rel": "What is a preamplifier?, What is a power amplifier?, Class AB amplifier"},
]
